**Correct: D.** Stratified random sampling of high-confidence extractions catches novel error patterns that confidence-based routing misses. New document formats, regulatory changes, or data drift can introduce errors the model is confidently wrong about. Ongoing sampling is the safety net that enables confident automation. **Why not A:** Past performance doesn't guarantee future accuracy — new document types, vendor format changes, or regulatory updates can introduce novel error patterns at any time. **Why not C:** Lowering the confidence threshold reduces review volume but still only reviews low-confidence extractions, missing errors in high-confidence ones. **Why not B:** Fixed random sampling is better than no review but unstratified sampling may undersample rare document types where errors are more likely.

</details>

**Q59 (Task 5.4).** Your extraction system requires operators to explore large document repositories to understand new document formats before configuring extraction pipelines. During an extended exploration session analyzing 200+ legal documents, the operator notices Claude starts giving inconsistent answers — referencing "typical contract patterns" rather than specific clauses discovered earlier in the session. Using /compact doesn't fully resolve the issue because key structural findings from early exploration are lost in summarization. What is the most effective approach?

